{
  "answer": "**The work is *Old English Elegies*, Chapter 4 (\"Leodum is minum swylce him mon lac gife;\").**[^1]\n\nThis chapter is a first-person lament known as \"Wulf and Eadwacer,\" matching the riddle-like description: the speaker notes that her people will devour \"him\" (Wulf) if he raids,[^2] states \"Our fates are not the same,\"[^3] describes Wulf on one island while she is on a \"fast\" island \"by fen surrounded,\"[^4] and abruptly addresses a second man named Eadwacer.[^5]\n\nThe requested quotation addressing him is:  \n\"Do you hear, Eadwacer? Our wretched whelp  \na wolf bears to the woods.\"[^5]\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 4](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/04-leodum-is-minum-swylce-him-mon-lac-gife/translation/).\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 4](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/04-leodum-is-minum-swylce-him-mon-lac-gife/translation/#p-1fe43f).\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 4](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/04-leodum-is-minum-swylce-him-mon-lac-gife/translation/#p-1fe43f).\n[^4]: *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 4](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/04-leodum-is-minum-swylce-him-mon-lac-gife/translation/#p-75b6cd).\n[^5]: *Old English Elegies*, [Chapter 4](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/04-leodum-is-minum-swylce-him-mon-lac-gife/translation/#p-7cd654).",
